    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying for my physics final and im kinda stuck on quantum entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? i dont need the heavy math right now just a conceptual explanation",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a bizarre phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are. When you measure a property of one entangled particle, you instantly know the corresponding property of the other particle, even if it's across the galaxy. The key difference from classical correlation is that this linkage is non-local and stronger than anything achievable through pre-arranged hidden variables; it's a genuine, instantaneous quantum connection. Think of it as a shared, probabilistic destiny rather than just knowing what you put in two separate, sealed boxes.",
      "source": "target",
