    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. i keep seeing people call it \"spooky action at a distance\" though. why do they call it spooky? is there something actually weird about the way the particles interact or is it just a metaphor?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Spooky action at a distance\" is the phrase Einstein used because it seems so counterintuitive to our everyday understanding of physics. It's spooky because the correlation appears to happen instantaneously, faster than light, which violates our classical notions of locality. However, it's not a literal communication channel that can be used to send messages faster than light, which is a crucial distinction. The weirdness lies in the *instantaneous correlation* itself, not in some hidden signal traveling between the particles.",
      "source": "target",
