    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "so if there's no signal actually traveling between them, how do they \"know\" what to do? it just feels like there's some kind of invisible, mysterious force or some hidden mechanism making them sync up perfectly the moment one is measured. is there any theory that explains that \"invisible\" part?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "This is where the concept truly pushes the boundaries of our intuition, and honestly, it's one of the biggest mysteries in physics. The prevailing view, supported by Bell's Theorem tests, is that there is no hidden classical mechanism or invisible force actively coordinating the particles after they become entangled. Instead, the particles exist in a single, shared quantum state until a measurement forces that shared state to \"collapse.\" It's not that they are secretly communicating; rather, they were never truly independent entities in the first place.",
      "source": "target",
